raw_events.text:
**The Signal**

The hum of the telescope control room was a familiar lullaby to Dr. Mira Patel. Alone most nights, she tracked distant stars from her perch atop Dekker Mountain Observatory. The only interruptions were the static bursts in her headphones, cosmic whispers she dreamed of translating.

One ink-black evening, an anomaly cut through the white noise—rapid pulses, too ordered to be randomness, too intricate to be chance. Mira’s heart stuttered as she isolated the transmission, fingers trembling over the dials. Across her monitor, lines of encrypted data scrolled with frenetic urgency.

She covertly saved the recordings, even as the Observatory director muttered about increased government protocols and new, watchful visitors. A black SUV had parked at the gate that afternoon. Mira ignored the flicker of fear in her stomach.

Each night, she pored over the files, coaxing patterns from chaos. Layer upon layer fell away: prime numbers, shapes, a diagram of a red dwarf star she knew from her charts. The message became a plea—coordinates, life-support schematics, biological stats—an SOS.

But there was more. At dawn, a coded warning: **TELL NO ONE. THEY WATCH.**

Mira scrambled to cover her digital tracks, but a crisp knock on her door made her freeze. Two agents, all frowns and credentials, requested "cooperation in a matter critical to national security." They left with copies of her logs, but not before Mira slipped backup files to a hidden drive.

Desperate, she posted an anonymized snippet on a global radio astronomy forum. Messages flooded in—the coordinates matched a faint, unmapped object in the outer solar system, emitting weak distress pulses. Strangers started amplifying and relaying her call, until the Observatory’s feed was abruptly cut.

The message was growing weaker; time was running out.

Heart pounding, Mira recalibrated a backup transmitter and, using the information the alien had provided, sent a narrow-beam response toward the coordinates: **“You are not alone. Help is coming.”**

Within hours, the original transmission faded forever.

Weeks passed with no sign of government agents and no new cosmic noise. But thousands now watched the night skies along with Mira, believing the truth she’d risked everything to reveal: a voice had called from the darkness, and—thanks to her—Earth had answered.
